truth and aboutness by stephen yablo immanuel kant lecture series events at stanford truth and aboutness by stephen yablo immanuel kant lecture series facebook twitter email print add to calendar the immanuel kant lecture series are an annual event organized by the stanford philosophy department and given by a distinguished philosopher this year's speaker is stephen yablo a professor of philosophy and linguistics at mit abstract lots of things stand in part whole relations material objects events words historical eras even sets why not propositions one might think a proposition p's parts are the propositions it implies but not any old true implication reflects favorably back on p otherwise snow is alive would be partly true by virtue of implying that snow is alive or white a certain notion of subject matter of what statements are about lets us identify p's parts more accurately some parts are extricable from their wholes as x is red can be pulled out of x is red and round leaving x is round as remainder while others are inextricable as x is red seems inextricable from x is scarlet this bears on a number of proposed philosophical explanations like the explanation of trying to raise my arm as what remains when we subtract from my raising it the fact that my arm actually went up when wednesday may 18 2011 5 30 pm approximate duration of 2 hour s where 320 105 braun geology corner stanford university map audience general public tags lecture reading humanities sponsor department of philosophy contact 650 723 25457 leniac stanford edu admission all events are free open to the public and wheelchair accessible permalink http events stanford edu events 281 28179 more info last modified may 13 2011
